Overview

The data is from the project How Department of Health (DOH) communicate about Covid-19 pandemic on 50 states and the Columbia Districts Facebook fan-pages? The research groups collected about 10000 posts about Covid-19 Pandemic. The content of the post were taken into consideration under two perspectives: information related (eg. provide number of case, what risk factors relevant to the spread out of Covid virus), and call to action related (eg. mask up, stay at home, get test, or get vaccine).

Using different Health Communication theories, the research generating 20 variables on risk communication, calls to actions on testing, vaccination, and actions to prevent Covid, and sympathy to lost due to Covid. Furthermore, the research also explores on to what extent health efficacy at collective-individual level and negative-positive outcome connotation have been mentioned.

Real_ID: the unique number assigned for each post to retreve if any information seems not right month: the month that the posts were posted state: abbreviation of the states names

Independent variables

Gov_poli: State governors political party

Trifecta: State government Trifecta is a term to describe single-party government, when one political party holds the governorship and majorities in both chambers of the state legislature

minority_percent: Percentage of minority people in states population

ProspertiyRanking: Rank of the states prosperity

Dependent variables

Mental_8_YesNo: Whether or not the posts mentioned mental health issues.

Pop_11_Number: Numbers of vulnerable groups (eg. minority people, senior people, ppl with pre health conditions) have been mentions in the posts.

RiskFactor_2_CTA: Call-to-actions related to Risk Factors

SocialDisparities_3_CTA: Call-to-actions on Social Disparities

Positive_14a_Number: Number of positive outcomes generated in the posts.

  • First of all, I wanted to plot a chart explaining the relationship between States Percentage of minority people and Number of groups of vulnerable populations were mentioned in the posts.
library(ggthemes)
p1 <- 
data51states2 %>% 
      drop_na(minority_percent) %>% 
      drop_na(Pop_11_Number) %>% 
      ggplot(aes(x= minority_percent, y= Pop_11_Number)) +
      geom_point(color = "red") + 
      scale_color_continuous(
      type = "viridis",
      limits = c(0,20), 
      breaks = c(0, 10, 20, 30, 40, 50)) +
      geom_smooth(method= "lm") + 
      labs(title = "Chart 1", 
           x = "Percentage of minority people", 
           y = "Number of Vulnerable population") +
     theme_economist()
p1
## `geom_smooth()` using formula 'y ~ x'

Interpretation: The state with Percentage of minority people from 20 - 40 % mentioned the vulnerable population with the highest number of groups, the state with lower than 20% and higher than 80% people are minority mentioned less vulnerable groups. However, most of the posts that mentioned these vulnerable groups mentioning 1-2 of them.

p3

Interpretation Generally, the states with Democratic Governors seems to generates posts with more positivie health outcome than states with Republican ones. However, the differences seems to be slight, more statistical tests needed to be performed to have concrete conclusion about the significance of the differences.

  • Often in text analysis, we will want to remove stop words, which are We can remove stop words words that are not useful for an analysis, typically extremely common words such as the, of, to, and so forth in English. We can remove stop words (kept in the tidytext dataset stop_words) with an anti_join().
dohtext2 <- 
dohtext1 %>%
  count(word, sort = TRUE) %>% 
   anti_join(stop_words)

dohtext3 <-

  filter(n > 1000) %>%
  mutate(word = reorder(word, n))

Retrospectives

It is very nice to use the tool that Ive learnt the last three month in exploring the real data pf a project that I am actually working on. I have also realized that it is nice to have some freedom to explore the data the way I wanted. However, I also found that there are two type of skills that I need to learn in the future: (1) using R for different statistical test and (2) using R for text mining. These are the two necessary skills for me to be better off as a communication researcher who want to work more on big data and text data using R language.
